ccompanying Germany’s transition from Nazism to liberal democracy. Tracing the activities of entrepreneurs, customers, government officials, and citizen-activists, Before Porn Was Legal brings to light the profound social, legal, and cultural changes that attended the growth of the erotica sector. Heineman’s innovative readings of governmental and industry records, oral histories, and the erotica industry’s products uncover the roots of today’s sexual marketplace and reveal the indelible ways in which sexual expression and consumption have become intertwined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBusinesswomenzGermanyvBiography. 0aPornographyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex-oriented businesseszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen-owned business enterpriseszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  apornography, erotica, sexuality, beate uhse, business, entrepreneur, businesswoman, birth control, rhythm method, black market, regulation, censorship, germany, postwar, widow, biography, church, religion, mail order, self-help books, sex aids, condoms, contraception, legalization, legislation, internet, sexual revolution, activism, social change, history, politics, law, nonfiction, gender, expression, consumption, women-owned businesses, prude, economics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022632521740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226325231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226325231/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles